05274nmm a2200673Ia 9789048563272DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20242024ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485632727 a10.1515/97890485632722doi  a(DE-B1597)680343  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aART0570002bisacsh00aSpaces :bExploring Spatial Experiences of Representation and Reception in Screen Media /ced. by Ian Christie. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (222 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Key Debates: Mutations and Appropriations in European Film Studies ;v900tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tEditorial -- tAcknowledgments -- tPART I Spaces of Spectatorship -- t2. Panoramic Space and the Mesdag Show -- t3. Places of Exhibition -- t4. Lockdown as a Mental Space of Communication -- tPART II Spaces on Screen -- t5. The Go-Between's Picturesque -- t6. Akerman and Domestic Space -- t7. Sequence and Simultaneity -- t8. Unhoused -- tPART III Spatial Speculations -- t9. Conjuring Spaces on Page and Screen - A Dialogue -- t10. Fly Me to the Moon ... Extra-Terrestrial Projections in Artists' Film and Video -- t11. Stereoscopic Space in Cinema -- t12. Of Drones and the Environmental Crisis in the Year 2020 -- t13. Afterword - Beyond the Frame: "Immersion," New Technologies and Old Ambitions -- tIndex of Film and Video Titles -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Subjects0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aFilm has long been defined as a temporal art, most famously by André Bazin and Andrei Tarkovsky. Yet more fundamentally it has always been a spatial art, transporting its audiences imaginatively to spaces and places other than those they literally inhabit. In the digital era, this spatial illusion and paradox has been greatly expanded - by the predominance of domestic film viewing, along with new extra-terrestrial perspectives, and the promise of novel kinesthetic experiences with Virtual Reality and "immersion". The international authors in this collection address the history and aesthetics of screen media as spatial transposition, in a range of exemplary analyses that run from the landscapes of John Ford's westerns to Chantal Akerman's claustrophobic domestic spaces, from the conventions of the English country house film to Patrick Keiller's Robinson roaming a changed country, and from the experiences of Covid pandemic confinement to those of un-homed van-dwellers in Chloe Zhao's award-winning NOMADLAND.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 4aFilm Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 4aTransnational and Global Studies. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  aSpacial art, screen media, virtual reality, film viewing, temporal art.1 aArmstrong, Isobel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroughton, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastro, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristie, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristie, Ian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCosgrove, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElwes, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeiller, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeperchey, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKernan, Luke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOdin, Rog